<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">The bay is at least four miles in circumference the land gently Rising from the water edge and terminating in <span class="DelHand-author">land</span><span class="AddHand-author">the</span> chain of Mountain from which the <span class="DelHand-author">S</span><span class="AddHand-author">C</span>ascades is a projection: and surely if ever Miltons beautiful description of "Shade above Shade a woody theatre," was realized, it is here<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  There are two Rocky Islands in the middle of the western channel which communicate with the main land by <span class="AddHand-author">a</span> reef on which there is not more than 3 or 4 feet water and precludes all enterance of Vessels from that quarter<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The south <span class="DelHand-author"><span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span></span> end of Grand Island is low and sandy but covered with herbage, on it, and an adjoining hill the Indians have their Huts<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The bay is directly opposite, where they put out their nets, and go a Spearing every calm night with flambeaux<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  They take as fine Trout and Whitefish as are found in any part of the Lake<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">From Grand Island bay the distance to Lake Michigan cannot be more than 60 or 70 miles as the Indians Sleep but one night on the Road when they use expedition which proves that the two Lakes Run for a certain distance nearly para<span class="AddHand-author">l</span>lel and approximate much more than they are made to do in any of the Maps we have Yet had of this Country<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[20]</span></p>

